## Pattern

👉 Sliding Window + Frequency Tracking (custom match counter)

---

## Recognition Trigger

```text id="n1"
find minimum substring
that contains all characters of another string
```

Think:

```text id="n2"
expand → check validity → shrink → track best window
```

---

# Core Idea (Your Style)

Instead of tracking:

```text id="n3"
unique characters satisfied
```

you track:

```text id="n4"
total required character matches (formed)
```

Where:

```text id="n5"
formed = number of characters from t that are currently satisfied in window
req = total characters in t (including duplicates)
```

---

# Data Structures

```cpp id="n6"
unordered_map<char,int> sub   // frequency of t
unordered_map<char,int> window // frequency of current window
```

---

# Key Invariant

A character contributes to `formed` only when:

```text id="n7"
window frequency is still <= required frequency
```

So:

```cpp id="n8"
if (window[c] < sub[c]) formed++;
```

This ensures you only count “useful matches”.

---

# Algorithm Flow (Your Logic)

## Step 1 — Expand Right Window

```text id="n9"
move right pointer
update window frequency
increase formed if useful match found
```

---

## Step 2 — Once valid window is formed

```text id="n10"
formed == req
```

Now try to shrink from left while keeping validity.

---

## Step 3 — Shrink Window

```text id="n11"
reduce window[left]
if removing breaks requirement → formed--
move left++
```

---

## Step 4 — Track Answer

```cpp id="n12"
update currAns when valid window is smaller
```

---

# Key Insight in YOUR APPROACH

You are not using:

```text id="n13"
formed = number of unique characters satisfied
```

Instead you use:

```text id="n14"
formed = total matched character occurrences
```

So validity condition becomes:

```text id="n15"
formed == length of t
```

---

# Complexity

### Time:

```text id="n16"
O(m + n)
```

* Each character enters window once
* Each character leaves window once

---

### Space:

```text id="n17"
O(k)
```

k = distinct characters

---

# Why Your Approach Still Works

Because you maintain:

```text id="n18"
correct match accounting (no overcounting)
+ correct decrement when window shrinks
```

So the invariant is preserved.

---

# Edge Case Handling (Important)

Your checks like:

```cpp id="n19"
if (sub[s[left]] > 0)
```

ensure:

```text id="n20"
only required characters affect formed
```

Good safeguard.

---

# Weakness of this style (not wrong, just tradeoff)

This approach:

```text id="n21"
mixes frequency tracking + validity + matching in one variable (formed)
```

So:

* harder to reason about
* more edge conditions
* easier to break when modifying

---

# Strong Pattern Version (for comparison)

Standard approach separates:

```text id="n22"
need count per character
+
formed = how many characters fully satisfied
```

Yours:

```text id="n23"
formed = total satisfied character matches
```

Both valid — just different abstraction levels.

---

# One-line Memory Hook (YOUR APPROACH)

```text id="n24"
Expand window, count useful matches, shrink when fully matched, track smallest valid window.
```
